## Implementation Plan: Adding 5 New File Inventory MCP Operations

Based on my thorough exploration of the `/worksp/monitor/app/apps/nas-mcp` directory, here is the exact architecture and recipe for adding your new operations.

---

## 1. Language & Layout

**Language:** TypeScript (strict ESM)  
**Entrypoint:** `/worksp/monitor/app/apps/nas-mcp/src/index.ts`

**Directory tree:**
```
apps/nas-mcp/
├── src/
│   ├── index.ts                 (405 lines) — MCP server factory, always-on tools, HTTP handler
│   ├── nas-client.ts            (176 lines) — HTTP client to nas-api, tier classification, HMAC signing
│   └── nas-tools.ts (symlink)   → ../../packages/shared/src/nas-tools.ts
│                                  (3651 lines) — ALL_TOOL_DEFS registry, TOOL_GROUPS, tool search/format
├── tools-config.json            (JSON) — Enable/disable read+write tools without rebuild
├── Dockerfile                   (multi-stage: builder + runner)
├── package.json                 (node:22 Alpine, zod + @modelcontextprotocol/sdk)
└── tsconfig.json               (strict, target=ES2022)
```

**Key path:** Tool definitions live in the **symlinked shared source** at `/worksp/monitor/app/packages/shared/src/nas-tools.ts`, not locally. This is the single source of truth for all 119 tool definitions.

---

## 2. The MCP Server & Exposed Tools

**Architecture:** Lazy-loaded registry with 5 always-on tools per session.

**ALL_TOOL_DEFS:** Defined at `/worksp/monitor/app/packages/shared/src/nas-tools.ts:127`, a single `McpToolDef[]` array containing all 119 read+write tool definitions.

**Exposed tools per session (always-on):**
1. `tool_search` — Discover tools by keyword
2. `invoke_tool` — Execute any registry tool by name + args
3. `run_command` — Free-form read-only shell (tier-1-only)
4. `check_disk_space` — Eager freebie (read tool, no round-trip needed)
5. `restart_nas_api` — Eager freebie (write tool, always available)

See `/worksp/monitor/app/apps/nas-mcp/src/index.ts:201–313` for registration.

**Why only 5?** MCP `tools/list` is cached by Claude Desktop on connect. Returning 119 tools (~50k tokens) vs 5 (~3k tokens) saves context. Tools not in the list are still discoverable and callable via `tool_search`+`invoke_tool`.

---

## 3. McpToolDef Shape (Complete)

**Interface definition:** `/worksp/monitor/app/packages/shared/src/nas-tools.ts:3–10`

```typescript
export interface McpToolDef {
  name: string;                                    // exact tool ID, e.g. "start_btrfs_scrub"
  description: string;                            // human text, prefixed with "WRITE —" if write:true
  write: boolean;                                 // true = state-modifying (tier 2/3), false = read-only (tier 1)
  params: Record<string, z.ZodTypeAny>;          // ZodRawShape: { target, filter, packageName, ... }
  buildCommand: (input: Record<string, unknown>) => string;  // Input validator + command builder
}
```

**Complete real example:** `start_btrfs_scrub` (write, tier 2)
```typescript
{
  name: "start_btrfs_scrub",
  description: "WRITE — Starts a Btrfs scrub on a volume to check data integrity. Pass the volume name (e.g. 'volume1') in filter, or leave empty to start scrub on all Btrfs volumes. Scrubs run in the background; use check_scrub_status to monitor progress.",
  write: true,
  params: { target, filter },
  buildCommand: (input) => {
    const volumeFilter = (input.filter as string | undefined)?.trim();
    if (volumeFilter) {
      const vol = volumeFilter.replace(/^\//, "").replace(/^btrfs\//, "");
      const btrfsPath = `/btrfs/${vol}`;
      return [
        `echo '=== STARTING BTRFS SCRUB: ${btrfsPath} ==='`,
        `btrfs scrub start ${quote(btrfsPath)} 2>&1`,
        `echo ''`,
        `echo '=== SCRUB STATUS ==='`,
        `btrfs scrub status ${quote(btrfsPath)} 2>&1`,
      ].join("\n");
    }
    return [
      `echo '=== STARTING BTRFS SCRUB (all btrfs volumes) ==='`,
      `found=0`,
      `for v in /btrfs/volume[0-9]*; do`,
      `  [ -d "$v" ] || continue`,
      `  found=1`,
      `  echo "Starting scrub on $v"`,
      `  btrfs scrub start "$v" 2>&1`,
      `  echo ''`,
      `done 2>/dev/null`,
      `[ "$found" -eq 0 ] && echo 'No btrfs volumes found at /btrfs/volume* — deploy update required (see docker-compose.agent.yml)'`,
    ].join("\n");
  },
}
```

